{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"64c16fb6-e969-4580-8884-7cd7e6436a02","content":"The standard approach is to introduce a **file system abstraction**:\n\n1. **Define an interface** wrapping the operations you use:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\n2. **Create a real implementation** for production:\n\n```csharp\npublic class FileSystem : IFileSystem\n{\n    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);\n    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);\n    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);\n}\n```\n\n3. **Inject `IFileSystem`** into classes that need it, then **mock it in tests**.\n\n**Alternatively**, the [`System.IO.Abstractions`](https://www.nuget.org/packages/System.IO.Abstractions) NuGet package provides a ready-made `IFileSystem` interface covering the full `System.IO` surface, plus a `MockFileSystem` for testing — saves you from maintaining your own wrapper.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"536c06f3-8ad2-4a11-a57b-039f292a0b88","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to make file system operations (`File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, `Directory.Exists`) testable in their .NET project. This is a design/architecture question, not a code change request. I should provide a concise answer about the common pattern for this.\n\nThe standard approach is to introduce a file system abstraction (interface) that wraps these calls, then inject it via dependency injection. This allows you to mock/stub the file system in tests.\n\nI don't need to use any tools for this - it's a general software engineering question I can answer directly.","outputTokens":429,"requestId":"E3FE:204F5C:2122D4F:24CA373:6A0535C3"},"id":"ccc4ae73-4b4e-4fdc-a3c1-1ec6b00daa4a","timestamp":"2026-05